<PART ID="packagefmt">
<TITLE>Package Format and Installation</TITLE>

<CHAPTER ID=swinstall>
<TITLE>Software Installation</TITLE>
<PARA></PARA>

<SECT1 ID=pkgformat>
<TITLE>Package Format</TITLE>
<PARA>
Applications should be provided in the RPM (Version 3) packaging format
with some restrictions listed below.
</PARA>
<PARA>
Distributions must provide a mechanism for installing applications in
the RPM (Version 3) packaging format with some restrictions listed
below.
</PARA>
<PARA>
<FOOTNOTE ID="pkg-1">
<PARA>
The distribution itself may use a different packaging format for its
own packages, and of course it may use any mechanism for installing the
RPMv3 packages that is available.
</PARA>
</FOOTNOTE>
</PARA>
<SECT2>
<TITLE>Package Format Description</TITLE>
<PARA>
A formal description of the 
<ulink url="http://www.rpmdp.org/rpmbook/node117.html">
RPM v3 package format 
</ulink> 
can be found in the appendix of 
<ulink url="http://www.rpmdp.org/rpmbook/">
Maximum RPM
</ulink> 
.

</PARA>
</SECT2>

<SECT2>
<TITLE>Package Script Constraints</TITLE>
<PARA>
Scripts used as part of the package install and uninstall may only use
commands and interfaces that are specified by the LSB. All other commands are
not guaranteed to be present, or behave in expected ways.
</PARA>

<PARA>
Packages may not use RPM triggers.
</PARA>

<PARA>
Packages may not depend on the order in which scripts are executed
(pre-install, pre-uninstall, &amp;c), when doing an upgrade.
</PARA>
</SECT2>

</SECT1>

<SECT1 ID=pkgtools>
<TITLE>Package Tools</TITLE>
<PARA>
The LSB does not specify the interface to the tools used to manipulate LSB
format packages. Each conforming distribution will provide documentation
for installing LSB format packages.
</PARA>

</SECT1>

<SECT1 ID=pkgnameconv>
<TITLE>Package Naming Conventions</TITLE>
<PARA>
Packages should follow these rules for creating their names. This will enable
the use of package dependencies by LSB conforming packages.
</PARA>

<SECT2>
<TITLE>Package Naming</TITLE>
<PARA>
Package names must be registered with the Linux Assigned Names And Numbers Authority.
</PARA>

</SECT2>

<SECT2>
<TITLE>Package Dependencies</TITLE>
<PARA>
Packages must depend on a dependency "lsb".  They may not depend on
other system-provided dependencies.  If a package includes "Provides"
it must only provide a virtual package name which is registered to
that application.
</PARA>

</SECT2>

</SECT1>

</CHAPTER>

